CRYO-WRAP PROTOCOL — TEMPORAL SEQUENCING
Why Cold First, Then Heat — and Why the Order is Non-Negotiable
THE SCIENCE During a migraine attack, the trigeminal nerve activates and triggers dilation of the meningeal blood vessels — the vessels lining the brain's protective membrane. It is these dilated, inflamed vessels pressing against sensitized trigeminal nerve tissue that produce the characteristic throbbing pain.
Cold (2–8°C) applied to the occipital and temporal arterial sites causes vasoconstriction — the active narrowing of dilated vessels. This directly reduces the mechanical pressure on trigeminal nerve tissue, interrupting the throbbing cycle at its vascular source.
Applying heat during this phase would cause vasodilation — actively worsening vessel dilation and amplifying pain. This is why generic "heat for headaches" advice fails during active attacks.
The 20-Minute Rule: After 20 minutes of cold therapy, the body triggers paradoxical vasodilation — a compensatory warming response that undoes vasoconstriction. Cold must be applied in 20-minute sessions with 10-minute breaks. Longer application is counterproductive.
THE CUSTOMER TRANSLATION "Your migraine throbs because blood vessels are swollen and pressing against sensitized nerve tissue. Cold shrinks them. The throbbing is pressure — cold removes the pressure. Heat would do the opposite."
When heat becomes appropriate: In the postdrome phase (after the attack), once vascular inflammation has subsided, gentle heat promotes parasympathetic recovery — muscle relaxation, improved circulation, and cortisol normalization. This is why the Neuro-Massager's heated modes are postdrome tools, not attack tools.
The store brief: The cold→heat sequencing must be explained on the product page and reinforced in the ebook. It positions CrownCalm as the brand that knows something your doctor didn't tell you — which is the most powerful trust-building statement a DTC brand can make.
COPY HOOK FOR THIS MECHANISM "Ice during the attack. Warmth after the storm. Most people do this backwards. Here's the exact sequence — and why it changes everything."
OPTIC SHIELD — SPECTRAL FILTRATION
FL-41 & the ipRGC Pathway — Why This Is Not a Blue-Light Filter
THE SCIENCE The human eye contains two photoreceptor systems. System 1 (rods and cones) processes visual information. System 2 — intrinsically photosensitive retinal ganglion cells (ipRGCs) — is hardwired not to visual processing but to the brain's pain and arousal centers.
ipRGCs contain a photopigment called melanopsin, which is maximally activated by blue-green light in the 480–520nm wavelength band. When ipRGCs fire, they signal directly to the thalamus, hypothalamus, and the trigeminal pain pathway — which is why bright light makes migraine pain worse, and why photophobia is a neurological symptom, not just discomfort.
Sub-visible flicker: AC-powered fluorescent and LED lighting flickers at 100–120 Hz. This is below the threshold of conscious visual perception — you cannot see it. But ipRGCs register it continuously. For a sensitized nervous system, 8 hours of office lighting is 8 hours of low-grade neurological stimulation filling the bucket.
FL-41 filtration targets the 480–520nm band specifically, blocking up to 80% of the light that activates the ipRGC pain pathway. Clinical studies show FL-41 reduced migraine frequency in pediatric patients from 6+ per month to fewer than 2 per month.
THE CUSTOMER TRANSLATION "Your eyes have a second nervous system behind them. It has nothing to do with seeing — it's directly wired to your brain's pain centers. Bright light activates it. FL-41 blocks the exact frequency that does the activating. The office lights you sit under for 8 hours are a low-grade migraine trigger you can't see or feel — until the bucket overflows."
The 15-minute adaptation window — critical education: FL-41 appears rose-pink on first wear. This is the single highest-risk return trigger. The page must explain: "The tint you see in the first 10 minutes is the visual cortex recalibrating its white balance. At 10–15 minutes, the tint recedes from consciousness. The filtration remains fully active. The pink is confirmation the filter is working — not a design flaw."
