ACOUSTIC SILENCE BUDS — AUDITORY MASKING
Brown Noise, Gate Control, and Why 30dB of Silence Changes the Neurological Equation
THE SCIENCE Sound is the most underestimated migraine trigger in consumer wellness. Phonophobia — sensitivity to sound — is a primary symptom of migraine sensitization, affecting over 80% of sufferers during attacks. But auditory load is also a pre-attack trigger: ambient noise continuously fills the sensory bucket even without conscious awareness of discomfort.
The Buds address auditory load on two levels simultaneously:
•	Passive attenuation (30dB): The seal-fit silicone tips physically block incoming sound waves before they reach the auditory nerve. 30dB converts an 80dB aircraft cabin (jet engine ambience) to approximately 50dB — the sound level of a quiet office. This is passive, mechanical, requires no power.
•	Active masking (Brown Noise): The 6mm micro-dynamic drivers deliver Brown Noise — a sound weighted heavily toward low frequencies (deep rumble, analogous to rain or distant thunder). Brown Noise provides environmental masking without the high-frequency content of White Noise, which becomes an auditory irritant for phonophobic listeners over extended sessions.
Why not White Noise: White Noise has equal energy at all frequencies, including high frequencies (hissing quality) that sensitized auditory systems register as a new stimulus. Brown Noise is physiologically quieter at the same masking effectiveness — it drops neurological load, not just perceived sound.
