CERVICAL AXIS MODULE — TRIGEMINOCERVICAL DECOMPRESSION
Why the Neck Is a Migraine Generator — and Why Cranial-Only Protocols Miss It
THE SCIENCE The upper cervical spine (C0–C2) converges directly onto the trigeminal nerve system at a structure called the trigeminocervical complex. Nerve fibers from the neck and nerve fibers from the trigeminal pathway feed into the same relay station in the brainstem — which is why cervical tension doesn't just cause neck pain. It lowers the threshold for the entire trigeminal pain cascade.
Tight suboccipital and upper trapezius musculature compresses the greater and lesser occipital nerves, which originate in the upper neck and run to the scalp. Compressed occipital nerves generate afferent bombardment — a continuous stream of low-grade nociceptive signal — that adds directly to the bucket, the same way sub-visible flicker or unmanaged ambient sound does. Cervical dysfunction is present in a large majority of migraine sufferers, either as a prodrome symptom or a co-occurring trigger, and becomes more common with age as cervical degeneration accumulates.
